darkfire orion 11/28/2020 11:33 AM
This does raise the question of what do the omnivores and carnivores eat in an anthropomorphic universe? Both "Bo Jack Horseman" and Karno's "The Rat King" answer this in an interesting yet dark way. In one Bo Jack Horseman episode, it is revealed that a large portion of the sentient chicken population is lobotomized and raised for food often, or at least in one such case, by their non-lobotomized counterparts. Karno's comic "The Rat King" follows a similar trend, focused through the lens of Herman Orca a rat living in the big city. Herman and other rats are viewed as second class citizens, ostracized, blocked from certain jobs, and only really kept alive as potential food. No rat is allowed to hold political office due to the fear that they would overturn certain policies and force other species into the position of being the next meal. Herman does not take to this system kindly and knows that before everyone threw him and his into the meat wagon the responsibility for feeding the carnivores was a societal obligation where all species gave up their dead to feed what some might call the social elite. This changes when other prey species started banning together and forced the predators to stop hunting or even eating their dead. The demand for meat was still the same though so the chickens and the rats were given up as a sacrifice to feed the predators. This question was also addressed in Beastars where it's revealed that a black market exists where predator species can buy the meat straight off the prey.
darkfire orion 11/28/2020 11:41 AM
The interesting part is how these parallel to modern society with the middle and upper-class if not "eating the poor" then at least agreeing that it is better than the alternative. This shows in the fear of every middle-class citizen, American or otherwise, that all it takes is one slip-up or law to turn them from a protected citizen to proverbial meat.
